# Download System Rules

Read `docs/download-system-requirements.md` before making changes to the
download pipeline. It contains the full specification, flow diagrams, and
invariants.

## Architecture

- **`src-tauri/src/helpers.rs`**: All testable pure/helper functions live here
  with `pub(crate)` visibility. Tests are in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` at the
  bottom of the file. Run `cargo test` in `src-tauri/` to verify.
- **`src-tauri/src/lib.rs`**: Tauri commands and wiring only. Imports helpers.
- **Provider cascade**: `download_clip()` loops through providers from
  `providers_for_url()`. Providers: `"ytdlp"` (default) and `"evil0ctal"`
  (Douyin/Kuaishou/Bilibili). See `DEFAULT_DOWNLOAD_PROVIDERS` in `src/types.ts`.

When adding new helper logic, put it in `helpers.rs` and add tests.
When adding a new download provider, add a `run_{name}_download()` fn and
a match arm in `download_clip()`'s provider loop.

## Cross-Platform Checklist

Before finishing any change to download-related code, verify:

- [ ] **Format selection**: `format_selection_for_url()` returns the correct
      `-f` arg per platform (Instagram uses `best`, others use
      `bestvideo+bestaudio/best`)
- [ ] **`--merge-output-format mp4`** is always present
- [ ] **macOS PATH**: sidecar and fallback both get `augmented_path()` via `.env("PATH", ...)`
- [ ] **Windows cookie workaround**: `apply_windows_cookie_workaround` runs before yt-dlp on Windows
- [ ] **Windows CREATE_NO_WINDOW**: system fallback uses `creation_flags(0x08000000)`
- [ ] **Cookie cascade**: retry order is browser → file → none (never skip the no-cookies fallback)
- [ ] **Provider cascade**: `providers_for_url()` returns valid list; providers with missing config are skipped
- [ ] **File discovery**: all providers use `{clipId}_` prefix so `find_downloaded_file` can find them
- [ ] **Range support**: `localfile://` protocol serves correct `Content-Range` headers
- [ ] **OS gates**: all platform-specific code uses `#[cfg(target_os = "...")]`
- [ ] **Tests pass**: run `cargo test` in `src-tauri/` and verify all pass

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Black videos on Windows/Instagram**: Instagram reports `vcodec: null`
   for h264 streams. Using `bestvideo+bestaudio` can select a VP9 DASH
   video-only stream → black video. Always use `format_selection_for_url()`
   which returns `best` for Instagram.

2. **"yt-dlp not found" in .app bundles**: macOS .app bundles don't
   inherit shell PATH. Always use `augmented_path()` and `find_system_ytdlp()`.

3. **Cookie DB locked on Windows**: Chromium locks Cookies SQLite. The
   copy-to-temp workaround in `apply_windows_cookie_workaround` is required.

4. **File not found after download**: If you change the `-o` template,
   update `find_downloaded_file` to match the new naming pattern.

5. **Duration probe fails**: `probe_duration` only works for MP4.
   Non-MP4 outputs will have `localDuration: None`.

## When Adding yt-dlp Arguments

- Check yt-dlp docs for cross-platform behavior differences
- Test the exact command line manually on both macOS and Windows
- Never add args that change the output container format without updating
  the `localfile://` MIME type list and `probe_duration`
- Add a test for any new URL-dependent logic in `helpers.rs`

## Error Messages

- User-facing yt-dlp outcomes go through `friendly_download_error()` (stderr **and** spawn / missing-binary errors from `run_ytdlp`)
- Add new patterns there when handling new failure modes
- Keep messages actionable (tell the user what to do, not what went wrong internally)
- Platform-aware: don't mention `brew` on Windows
